\begin_layout Section
Exponential Growth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 is a function that satisfies the differential equation
\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\dl}{\mathrm{d}}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\abs}[1]{\left|#1\right|}
\end_inset


\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\e}{\mathrm{e}}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f'(t)=k\,f(t),\label{eq:diffeq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is some fixed number.
 Let us also assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 only ever takes positive values â€“ for example,
 it may represent the quantity of some bacteria over time (that we assume never completely dies),
 or it may represent the amount of radioactive material in a sample which never quite becomes inert.
 Then,
 we wish to draw a conclusion about the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here is a possible argument.
 First,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 is never zero,
 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diffeq"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 we can conclude
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f'(t)}{f(t)}=k,
\]

\end_inset

for all time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Now we consider,
 for a fixed (but arbitrary) value 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

,
 the quantity
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{T}\frac{f'(t)}{f(t)}\,\dl t.\label{eq:qt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

On the one hand,
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{f'(t)}{f(t)}=k$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 this is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{T}k\,\dl t=kT$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand,
 via a 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

-substitution with 
\begin_inset Formula $u=f(t)$
\end_inset

,
 we obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{T}\frac{f'(t)}{f(t)}\,\dl t=\int_{f(0)}^{f(T)}\frac{1}{u}\,\dl u=\ln\abs{f(T)}-\ln\abs{f(0)}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus,
 we reach the conclusion that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:qt"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is at once equal to both 
\begin_inset Formula $Tk$
\end_inset

 and to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\abs{f(T)}-\ln\abs{f(0)}$
\end_inset

,
 and so these two quantities must be the same as each other.
 In other words:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln\abs{f(T)}-\ln\abs{f(0)}=kT.
\]

\end_inset

Since we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 is always a positive number,
 we can forego the absolute values,
 yielding
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ln f(T)-\ln f(0)=kT,
\]

\end_inset

and this equation may be solved for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 to obtain
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(T)=f(0)\,\e^{kT}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a fixed but arbitrary number,
 we reach the conclusion:
 Whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

 is a positive-valued function that satisfies the differential equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diffeq"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 it must be of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(t)=A\,\e^{kt},\label{eq:sol}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is some positive constant that represents the initial value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(t)$
\end_inset

.
 We also need to verify (but this is easy enough by direct calculation) that every such function does satisfy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diffeq"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.Thus,
 we concluded:
\end_layout

